24/02/2026

unix Commands :
1. Files & Directories :

ls

ls - shows list of files
ls -a -shows hidden files
ls -l  - shows complete detials about files 
ls -la  - shows hidden files complete detials about files  
ls -t   - shows files sorted by time
ls -r  - it shows reverse order 
ls -lt - it shows latest files first
ls -R - it shows all directories and also show the inside files of repository 
ls -S - sort by file size

pwd

pwd -p - shows the physical directory
pwd -L - show local directory(default)

cd

cd	 (or) cd ~       - Go to home directory
cd ..		     - Go back one folder
cd ../..       - Go back two folders
cd -	           - Go to previous directory and shows that line 
cd /	     - Go to root directory

mkdir - create a directory
rmdir - it removes directory if it is empty
touch - it creates a empty file and update time
cp - copy directories and files
mv - move & rename files and directories
rm - remove files and directories
stat - shows the file information 
find - is used to search perticular files and directories


2.File 

cat - it displays file contant 
less - it shows a file page by page
       ESC, :wq  to exit
more - shows file 
head - shows first lines of a file (default 10)
tail - shows last lines of a file (default 10)
tail -f -it shows live of a file
        ctr + c to exit 
nano - used to edit text in a file(first time we need to install it using apt install nano)
       ctr + x to exit
vi/vim - advanced text editor
       - vim file.txt - open file
       - "i" = then it turns insert mode we can add or remove text
       - "ESC" = to exit insert mode 
       - ":wq" = it give save file and exit
       - ":q!" = exit without saving



25/02/2026

grep

grep - used to search a word or pattern inside a file
grep "IT" hello.txt - it gives all "IT" department employee data
grep -i "it" hello.txt - ignore case sensitive
grep -n "Pune" hello.txt - it shows line number where the data is present
grep -r "HR" . - it shows which directory that column present
grep -v "Name" hello.txt - it can remove the mentioned data and gives remaining data
grep -c "IT" hello.txt - It counts the matching data and returns the number of matches.

SED 

sed 's/Name/name' hello.txt - replace the word
sed 's/Name/name/g' hello.txt - replace all "Name" in that file globally
sed -n '2p' hello.txt - shows only 2 lines
sed -n '2,5p' hello.txt - shows inbetween files like range
sed '3d' hello.txt - delete line 3
sed -i 's/hello/hi/g' hello.txt - replaces the word "hello" with "hi" in the file permanently

AWK

awk '{print $0}' hello.txt - it gives all data inside the file
awk '{print $1,$4}' hello.txt - it prints the 1st and 4th columns from the file
awk '{print NR,$1}' hello.txt - it gives line number before that column data
awk '{print NF}' hello.txt - it gives number of colums per line
awk '$4 > 50000 {print $4}' hello.txt - it prints the values in column 4 that followed by condition from the file
       Note : If we do not specify {print $4}, prints the all columns that satisfy the condition.
awk -F "," '{print $2}' hello.txt - it gives comma seperated data

CUT

cut -d " " -f2 hello.txt - it gives only 2nd column data (it works on space seperated data)
cut -d "," -f2 hello.txt - it gives only 2nd column data (it works on comma seperated data)
cut -d " " -f1,3 hello.txt - it gives 1,3 column data
cut -c1-5 hello.txt - give upto 5 characters on that data(it count spaces also)

SORT

sort hello.txt - it will sort based on 1st column default.
cat hello.txt | sort - sort the file using pipe
sort -r hello.txt - it will sort file and reverse the output
sort -n hello.txt - it will sort based on numerical column
sort -k3 hello.txt - it can sort specific column
sort -u hello.txt - used to remove duplicates and sort the file

uniq

uniq - it only work only if the duplicate data are next to each other otherwise it shows all data to avoid that we use "sort" and "pipe"
sort hello.txt | uniq = it works correctly and sort data
sort hello.txt | uniq -c - count duplicates
sort hello.txt | uniq -u - shows uniq data only duplicated data not shown( like i/p = 1,1,2,3 .o/p =2,3)
sort hello.txt | uniq -d - shows only duplicated data

WC

wc hello.txt - it gives in the format of no.of lines,words,characters
wc -c hello.txt - gives no.of character count
wc -l hello.txt - gives no.of lines count
wc -w hello.txt - gives no.of words count
wc -m hello.txt - gives no.of character/bytes count
grep "IT" hello.txt |wc -l - wc using pipe

TR

tr works with standard input,so we used " l "
echo "hello word" | tr 'h' 'H' - it replaces the character
echo "hello word" | tr 'a-z' 'A-Z' - it convert lowercase to uppercase
echo "hello word 12334" | tr -d '0-9' - used to delete numeric values
echo "hello word1234234" | tr -d 'a-z' 'A-Z' - used to delete alphabetical values
echo "hello word    1234234" | tr -s ' ' - used to remove extra spaces
cat hello.txt | tr 'a-z' 'A-Z' - used to change type of all data in file

TAR

tar - (tape archive) used to create archive multiple files into single file
       c-create archive
       v-show process
       f-file name
       x- archive file
       z-gzip compression
       j- bzip2 compression
tar -cvf hello.txt - it archive directory
tar -xvf hello.txt - it extract the file
tar -tvf hello.txt - list archive content
tar -czvf home.gz hello.txt/ - used to create compressed archive folder (tar +gzip)
tar -xzvf home.gz - compresses archive files


gzip 

gzip - used to compress files to reduce size
gzip hello.txt - it compress file of hello.txt.gz (original file replaced to compressed file)
gzip -k hello.txt - it keep original file and create new .gz file
gzip -l hello.txt.gz - to check compression file (mobaxterm does not support)

gunzip

gunzip hello.txt.gz - it decompress file
gzip -d hello.txt.gz -  it decompress file (alternate method of above command)

zip - compress multiple files
    zip we need to install : apt install zip (but not available in mobaxterm)

zip backup.zip a.txt b.txt -it compress both files into one zip file named backup
zip -r komhar.zip komhar/ - folder convert into .zip folder ( -r used to include folder files)

unzip 
unzip backup.zp - extract files from .zip

PROCESS MANAGEMENT

ps - shows current running processes

       PID - process ID
       TTY - Terminal
       TIME - CPU time used
       CMD - command name
       

ps -e - show all processes (or) ps -A
ps -ef - shows detail process list
       UID -user
       PPID - parent process

top
       - it is used to show livesystem process
      q- quit
      k-kill process
      s-sort by cpu
      m-sort by memory
      ctrl +c - exit command

htop -improved version of top
      we need to install in first "apt install htop"
kill pid(ex: 123) - it can stop using pid
   -9 -force kill
   -15 - stop (default)

killall - used instead of pid
killall crome - stop all crome processes

bg
    it is used to resume a stopped file in background
sleep 100 then press ctrl+z -it stops the process then run bg - process runs background

fg - it takes background job into foreground

jobs -shows background jobs
 [1] -job number
 & -background process

nohup - it allows a process to continue running even if the terminal is closed

nohup cat hello.txt & - it runs continues even if i logout from server 
               we can stop this using kill command

DF

df - it shows disk space, used space and available space
df -h -human readable format
*
df -h/home - check specific file system

du - it shows how much space files occupied
du -h  - human readable
du -sh a.txt-shows directory total size
*
du -h --max-depth=1  - shows size of all folders
* 
free -show ram and swap memory usage
free -h - human readable
*
free -h -s 2 - it shows continues memory monitoring

*
mount - it attach a filesystem to the linux directory
mount usb device -sudo mount/dev/sdb1/mnt -
*
umount - removes the mounted filesystem safely
         must umount before removing usb

umount device
*

cal - used to display calender in terminal
cal 2 2026 - it shows 2 nd moth calender of 2026 in terminal
cal 2026 - it shows all 12 months on that year
cal -3 - it shows 3 months calender
cal -m - to start with monday (default it contains sunday)
cal -v - it shows vertical calender

hostname -it shpws server name in the network
sudo hostname newserver - used to change host name temporary
whoami - used to show current logged -in user
who - used to show all users currently login into the system
uptime - shows how long the system has been running snice last time the system was started
date - shows date and time
date "+%Y-%m-%d" - custom date format(shows date only)
date "+%H-%M-%s" - shows time only




26/02/2026

13. System Info

whoami                          - it shows current user
echo "Current user: $(whoami)"  - it shows the current user like " current user: guru"
who -b - it shows               - it show the when the system was last started
                                     * but in linux not show any output because MobaXterm does not maintain real Linux boot records.
who                             - (it shows empty) shows currently who logged into the system 
id                              - it shows user identity information
                                     uid - user id
                                     gid - group id
                                     groups- groups the user belongs to
w                               - it shows logged in user and activity


hostname                        - Displays system host name
hostname -f                     - shows full domain name
hostname -i                     - shows ip address
                                   * but it not support mobaxterm 
                                      ipconfig - alternate of hostname -i
hostname -I                    - shows all ip address
                                     * but it not support mobaxterm 
                                      ipconfig - alternate of hostname -i
date                           - shows current date and time
date +%F                       - shows only date
date +%T                       - shows only time
date "+%d-%m-%y %H-%M-%s"      - custom format
date -s                        - used to set date and time (admin) 
                                   * not work in mobaxterm alternate is sudo date -s"2026-02-26 01:30:00"
uptime                         - shows how long system has been running since last boot
uptime -p                      - shows a simple human-readable format
uptime -s                      - when system is running

cal 2026                       - shows calender in specific year
cal 2 2026                     - show specific month in a year

